name: isopropylidene malonate
Reason: The basic unit for isopropylidene malonate is acetic acid, which has a melting point of about 16.6 degrees Celsius. The molecule has two ester groups, which typically raise the melting point due to their polar nature and the ability to form dipole-dipole interactions, by approximately 40-60 degrees each. It also has an isopropylidene group (a geminal dimethyl substitution on a single carbon) that can influence the melting point; geminal dimethyl groups typically raise the melting point by about 10-20 degrees due to the increase in van der Waals interactions from the additional methyl groups, but they also add steric hindrance which might slightly reduce the melting point again. Additionally, the cyclic structure of isopropylidene malonate will significantly restrict rotation about the ester bonds, increasing the thermal stability and raising the melting point compared to similar open-chain esters.
